	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Food aid too limited to support national food security</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>There is an ongoing discussion in the WTO and elsewhere on whether food aid is ‘part of the solution’ or ‘part of the problem’ when it comes to supporting national food security. A study has been published by ICTSD arguing that food aid is now too limited in scale to have much impact either way. Global food aid levels declined from 7.9 to 5.8 million tonnes between 2005 and 2007 and, despite a small rise in 2008, have since continued to decline. According to the report, the current scale of food aid ‘makes it an inadequate tool for supporting national food security, simultaneously, except in a few smaller economies.’ Current food aid levels are ‘barely adequate to respond to idiosyncratic risks in small and medium-sized economies that are uncorrelated with events elsewhere’.</p><p>This is a far cry, the study notes, from the 1994 Marrakesh Decision at the end of the GATT Uruguay Round which saw food aid as part of a new rules-based system for agricultural trade that could protect the interests of poor, net food-importing countries following liberalisation. The ICTSD study has been produced to inform debate as a number of key deadlines approach. As some of the deadlines in the Doha Round – on which negotiations have long been stalled – approach rapidly, there is discussion in Geneva on the role that food aid could play in moving the agricultural negotiations forward. The deadlines include the target date of 2013 for developed country Members of the WTO to eliminate agricultural export subsidies.</p><p>The current Food Aid Convention will expire in June 2012. The International Grains Council has been hosting negotiations on a successor convention between donors that account for four-fifths of international food aid. This might increase minimum commitments, but as the negotiations have been held ‘entirely in private’ there is not yet any guidance of what a new regime might offer.&nbsp;</p><p>If food aid were increased substantially, the report confirms that it would to be provided within a framework of rules that avoid trade distortions. Some WTO Members, notably the Cairns Group, are concerned that rich countries will use food aid as a way to circumvent new disciplines on export subsidies and disrupt their commercial trade. The report sees the new Food Aid Convention as one arena within which to establish such rules, but notes that ‘WTO agreements are both more generally applicable … and the disciplines would be potentially more robust than non-binding agreements.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ICTSD, ‘Trade policy options for enhancing food aid effectiveness’, by E. Clay, <i>Issue Paper</i> No. 41, May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/downloads/2012/05/trade-policy-options-for-enhancing-food-aid-effectiveness.pdf" target="_blank">http://ictsd.org/downloads/2012/05/trade-policy-options-for-enhancing-fo...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Many ACP states are net food-importing countries, and none are substantial exporters of the commodities most frequently provided as food aid. They tend, therefore, to have different interests to the Cairns Group of countries that style themselves as ‘non-subsidising exporters’, though compromise is sometimes possible in support of a shared interest elsewhere on the Doha agenda. The ICTSD report suggests that the interests of neither group are currently being well-served. Food aid was supposed to be part of the defence for poor net food importers against any increased world prices resulting from agricultural liberalisation by larger, richer states.&nbsp;</p><p>The agricultural liberalisation agreed in the Uruguay Round ran its course in the early and middle years of the last decade and so cannot have contributed directly to the world grain price hikes of the last few years. But the falling volumes of food aid, to levels that are inadequate other than to offset shortages in a few small and medium countries at the same time, does not give confidence to ACP and other net food importers that a new Doha Round of liberalisation would protect their interests. This, in turn, makes it harder for Latin American and other Cairns Group states to form a common position in Geneva with the ACP. More food aid and more controls on its use to prevent market disruption would be in the interest of both groups.</p>
		</div>
		
